## Decision Matrix

| Criteria | React Native | Flutter |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| **Learning Curve** | Low (if you know React) | Medium (need to learn Dart) |
| **Performance** | Good (native UI) | Excellent (compiled) |
| **Development Speed** | Fast | Fast |
| **Community** | Large, mature | Growing rapidly |
| **Third-party Libraries** | Extensive | Growing |
| **Platform Feel** | Native look and feel | Custom UI (can look native) |
| **Code Sharing** | High | High |
| **Hot Reload** | Yes | Yes |
| **Debugging** | Good tools | Excellent tools |
| **App Size** | Smaller | Larger |

## When to Choose React Native

- Your team already knows React/JavaScript
- You need maximum code sharing with web
- You want native platform look and feel
- You need extensive third-party library support
- You're building content-heavy apps

## When to Choose Flutter

- You want consistent UI across platforms
- Performance is critical
- You're building complex animations
- You want Google's backing and roadmap
- You're okay with learning Dart

## Conclusion

Both frameworks are excellent choices for cross-platform development. React Native excels in developer familiarity and ecosystem maturity, while Flutter offers superior performance and UI consistency. Consider your team's expertise, project requirements, and long-term maintenance when making your decision.

The mobile development landscape continues to evolve, and both frameworks are actively maintained with regular updates and improvements.
